Synthetic NEMSIS v3.5 PatientCareReport — isolated cervical SCI from a
shallow-water diving accident at a public pool. Multi-section, realistic
ePCR shape.

Profile: 24-year-old male, dove into shallow end and struck pool floor
head-first. Found prone in water by lifeguard, extricated by bystanders.
Conscious throughout (GCS 15) but reports loss of sensation/motor in
all four extremities. C-spine immobilized on scene. Receiving Level I
trauma center.

What this exercises beyond the polytrauma fixture:
- Mechanism is a "fall" via ICD-10 W16 (jumping/diving) — exercises the
  fall ICD-10 prefix table, not the MVC path.
- eSituation.07 carries ICD-10 S14.111A (cervical SCI, complete) — should
  flip spinal_injury_suspected even with GCS 15 + non-blunt-MVC mechanism,
  because impression overrides physiology.
- eInjury.09 carries Step 2 paralysis criterion (4509027) — should pin
  Level 1 activation despite stable vitals.
- eMedications.03 has methylprednisolone (high-dose steroid for SCI) —
  not a reversal agent or hemorrhage tx, must NOT trip those signals.
- Demonstrates the case where a patient with NORMAL physiology has
  catastrophic injury and the trace makes that visible.
-->
